<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>SSDI vs. SSI: Key Differences</h1>
  <h2>Basis for Eligibility</h2>
  <p><strong>SSDI</strong> is based on your work history and Social Security taxes paid. You must have sufficient work credits. <strong>SSI</strong> is need-based — it requires limited income and resources regardless of work history. Both require a qualifying disability.</p>
  <h2>Benefit Amount</h2>
  <p><strong>SSDI</strong> benefit varies based on your earnings history (average ~$1,537/month in 2025). <strong>SSI</strong> pays a flat federal benefit rate ($967/month for individuals, $1,450 for couples in 2025), with state supplements in some states.</p>
  <h2>Health Insurance</h2>
  <p><strong>SSDI</strong> comes with Medicare after a 24-month waiting period. <strong>SSI</strong> recipients are immediately eligible for Medicaid in most states.</p>
  <h2>Can You Receive Both?</h2>
  <p>Yes — if your SSDI benefit is low enough, you may qualify for both SSDI and SSI simultaneously (called "concurrent benefits"). SSI fills the gap up to the federal benefit rate.</p>
  <h2>Work Incentives</h2>
  <p><strong>SSDI</strong> has a Trial Work Period and Extended Period of Eligibility. <strong>SSI</strong> has a different work incentive structure — $1 of SSI is reduced for every $2 of earned income above $85/month.</p>
</BaseLayout>
